<h1 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold text-white mb-2 leading-tight">Psychology of Scrabble</h1>
<p class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-8 not-prose">2-letter words · 3-letter words · Dictionary</p>

<p class="text-sm text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 mb-6">Published June 15, 2026 · 6 min read</p>

<p class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300 mb-8">Scrabble isn't purely a vocabulary contest — it's a battle of composure, observation, and emotional control. The player who stays calm after drawing UUIIOW while their opponent bingos will outlast the genius who crumbles under pressure. Here's how to sharpen the mental edge that separates club players from champions.</p>

<h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Understanding Tilt</h2>

<div class="not-prose my-6 p-4 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
  <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center justify-center gap-6 text-center">
    <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">73%</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Players report tilt affects scores</p></div>
    <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">30–50</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Points lost per tilted game</p></div>
    <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">3 turns</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Avg recovery time from tilt</p></div>
  </div>
</div>

<p>Tilt is the emotional state where frustration overrides rational play. It commonly triggers after an opponent's unexpected bingo, drawing all vowels or all consonants, losing a challenge, or watching your planned spot get blocked.</p>

<div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 gap-4">
  <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
    <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Breathe between turns:</span> Take 3 seconds before looking at your rack after an opponent's big play. This tiny pause prevents reactive decisions and resets your focus to what you can control.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
    <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Accept variance:</span> Even the best rack can draw poorly. Treat bad draws as puzzles to solve, not injustices to protest. The bag doesn't know who you are — it's random, and that randomness evens out over tournaments.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
    <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Score the situation, not the emotion:</span> After an opponent bingos, ask "what's the spread now?" rather than "that's unfair." Quantifying the deficit makes it manageable — a 50-point gap is recoverable in 3-4 turns.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Reading Your Opponent</h2>

<p>Competitive Scrabble rewards observation. Your opponent's behaviour gives away information about their rack, their plans, and their confidence level.</p>

<div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
  <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
    <p class="text-green-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-2">Long hesitation</p>
    <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Often means they're weighing a bingo attempt or a risky phoney. They have options but aren't sure which is best.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-blue-500/30 bg-blue-950/10">
    <p class="text-blue-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-2">Quick confident play</p>
    <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">They planned this move while you were thinking. Usually means a strong rack with clear best option.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/10">
    <p class="text-purple-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-2">Tile exchange</p>
    <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Signals a terrible rack — multiple duplicates or vowel-consonant imbalance. Expect a weaker play next turn.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
    <p class="text-amber-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-2">Defensive short plays</p>
    <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Playing 2-3 letter words near premium squares suggests they're protecting a lead or denying you access.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="not-prose my-6 p-4 rounded-xl border border-indigo-500/30 bg-indigo-950/10">
